<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-141-092  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 141 092.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  March 20 1989 v6 n11 p1(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Developers dump hosts for PC LANs. (microcomputer local areanetworks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Breidenbach, Susan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A growing number of users, lured by the power and graphicscapabilities of intelligent workstations and the increasingavailability of automated software development tools, are shiftingtheir software development efforts away from large host systems tolocal networks.andP;  These users are looking at the mainframe as adata depository from which they can download information to localnetworks of microcomputers.andP;  Nova Biomedical Corp is one companythat develops software on 35 microcomputers that are linked in alocal network with three file servers.andP;  The migration of softwaredevelopment from hosts to standalone microcomputers was spurred bythe emergence of computer-aided software engineering (CASE) tools,which automate structuring techniques and the creation of dataflow diagrams.andP;  CASE tools are limited, however, in that they donot offer multiuser support for large-scale projects.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersLocal Area NetworksSoftware EngineeringComputer-Aided Software EngineeringIndustry AnalysisSoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>